\chapter{Systematically Elucidating miRNA Network Architecture in Disease}
\label{chp:systematically-elucidating-mirna-network}


\section{Disease}
\label{sec:disease}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

Traditional miRNA research has predominantly relied on single-molecule profiling, measuring

expression levels of individual miRNAs and correlating these with phenotypes or clinical

outcomes \cite{hammond2010american} . While this reductionist approach has generated valuable insights, it faces

fundamental limitations \cite{penaultl2012patholog} . Single-molecule analyses are susceptible to inter-sample

heterogeneity, often resulting in poor reproducibility across independent cohorts \cite{kumar2023impact,yang2024role} .

Furthermore, they cannot capture the emergent properties that arise from collective regulatory

interactions \cite{loh2019regulato} . Network analysis offers a complementary perspective that views miRNAs as

interconnected nodes within regulatory circuits, revealing stable topological features that are

more robust to biological noise than individual molecular measurements \cite{fuchswig2018target} . Biological

networks encode information in two fundamental components: nodes and edges. Nodes

represent individual molecular entities — in the context of miRNA networks, these include

miRNAs, their target mRNAs, and upstream regulators such as transcription factors. Edges

represent the regulatory relationships connecting these molecules, the functional interactions

through which miRNAs exert their biological effects \cite{tian2022comparat} . While nodes are characterized by

quantitative properties such as expression level and abundance, edges encode qualitative and

quantitative information about regulatory coupling, including interaction strength, directionality,

and context specificity. Both components contribute to network function, yet current research

predominantly focuses on nodal properties \cite{lai2016understa} .

Edge information in miRNA networks operates at two distinct layers. The first layer comprises

individual edges — specific miRNA-target interactions (MTIs) that represent discrete regulatory

relationships. The strength and activity of these individual edges carry functional information,

including clinical relevance for disease prognosis. The second layer comprises edge patterns, the

overall topology of how a miRNA connects to multiple targets and pathways. These topological


patterns encode functional context that determines how the same miRNA can exhibit different

behaviors across biological settings \cite{assidick2022targetin} . Systematic analysis of both layers is essential for

comprehensive network understanding. Despite the conceptual importance of edge information,

current miRNA research exhibits a systematic node-centric bias. Expression profiling studies

focus on identifying differentially expressed miRNAs, treating expression level as the primary

functional readout \cite{kalecky2020integrat} . Prognostic models typically use miRNA expression signatures, ignoring

the regulatory relationships that determine biological impact. Functional studies often identify

targets without systematically analyzing the network architecture that shapes regulatory output.

This bias leaves substantial information unexploited, the regulatory coupling between miRNAs

and targets, the topological context that modulates function, and the network-level properties

that distinguish functionally important miRNAs.

This chapter aims to demonstrate the unique value of edge-centric network analysis through two

complementary case studies. The first case study validates the clinical utility of individual edges,

showing that MTI-based prognostic modeling outperforms expression-based approaches in

triple-negative breast cancer. The second case study validates the functional interpretive power

of edge patterns, demonstrating that network topology explains the context-dependent functional

duality of hub miR-483 across diseases. Together, these studies establish an edge-centric

analytical paradigm that provides the methodological foundation for extending network analysis

to dynamic modifications in Chapter 4.


\section{Case I: Improving Prognostic Accuracy via edge information}
\label{sec:case-i-improving-prognostic-accuracy-vi}


\subsection{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

Triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC) is defined by the absence of estrogen receptor,

progesterone receptor, and HER2 expression, representing approximately 15-20% of breast

cancers \cite{zagami2022triple} . TNBC exhibits aggressive clinical behavior with high rates of recurrence and

metastasis, and lacks the targeted therapeutic options available for hormone receptor-positive or

HER2-amplified subtypes \cite{li2022identifi} . Patient outcomes are highly heterogeneous, creating urgent need


for robust prognostic biomarkers \cite{hsu2022survival} . However, the substantial inter-patient molecular

heterogeneity characteristic of TNBC poses significant challenges for biomarker development,

as individual molecular features often fail to replicate across independent cohorts.

We hypothesized that miRNA-target interaction scores, which capture the functional coupling

between miRNAs and their targets, would provide more robust prognostic information than

miRNA expression levels alone. This hypothesis is grounded in the reasoning that regulatory

relationships represent the functional output of miRNA activity, whereas expression levels only

indicate molecular abundance. If edges encode stable clinical information, MTI-based models

should demonstrate superior predictive accuracy and better generalization across patient cohorts

compared to expression-based approaches.


\subsection{Materials and Methods}
\label{sec:materials-and-methods}


\section{Data collection}
\label{sec:data-collection}

Gene and miRNA expression profiles, as well as clinical data of patients with triple-negative

breast cancer, were collected from two public datasets: TCGA\_BRCA data from The Cancer

Genome Atlas (TCGA) \cite{abudour2024role} and GSE19873 data from Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO,

http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/). These datasets encompass the expression profile of tumor

tissues and adjacent normal tissues from breast cancer patients across subtypes. According to the

clinical immunohistochemistry results, samples from TCGA and GEO with negative status for

ER, HER2, and PR were selected as TNBC samples for further study \cite{agarwal2015predicti} .


\section{Differential expression analysis of miRNAs and mRNAs}
\label{sec:differential-expression-analysis-of-mirn}

DESeq2 was used to analyze the differential expression of RNA-Seq data and miRNA-Seq data

from the TCGA\_TNBC dataset \cite{abudour2024role} . Differentially expressed miRNAs (DEmiR) were selected

based on the following criteria: Benjamini-Hochberg adjusted p-value < 0.01 with average |log2

Fold Change| $\geq$ 1 and baseMean (the average of gene expression across all samples) $\geq$ 50.

Differentially expressed mRNAs were selected based on adjusted p-value < 0.01, an average

|log2 Fold Change| $\geq$ 1, and baseMean (the average gene expression across all samples) $\geq$ 100.


\section{Learn miRNA and mRNA regulatory correlation by neural network}
\label{sec:learn-mirna-and-mrna-regulatory-correlat}

The expression patterns of miRNA can be learned from the expression level of mRNA if the

tight regulation between miRNAs and genes exists. A method based-on a four-layers neural

network called HubmiR \cite{abudour2024role} was previously developed by our team to learn the expression

pattern of miRNAs from mRNA in terms of pairing expression profiles retrieved from the

TCGA database \cite{abudour2024role} among 33 types of cancers. It was tested to be robust and generalizable on

both bulk and single-cell sequencing datasets. The contrast value of predicted miRNA

expression between TNBC tissues and normal breast tissues was calculated to identify miRNAs

playing a key role in TNBC regulation. miRNAs with contrast value >= 0.7 were selected for

further analysis.


\section{Selection of the prognosis-related miRNAs}
\label{sec:selection-of-the-prognosis-related-mirna}

First, the tumor stage (T-stage), metastasis stage (M-stage), node stage (N-stage), survival time

and event of the TNBC sample were analyzed by univariate Cox regression and Random Forest

algorithm to identify which feature is most associated with the TNBC patients’ survival outcome.

By applying Random Forest Combination, miRNAs above the 85th percentile were selected as

key features for T-stage classification. Intersections of selected miRNAs across TCGA datasets,

HubmiR and Random Forest Combination were regarded as hub miRNAs of TNBC. To

determine the superior set of miRNAs for prognostic prediction, Random Forest, and CatBoost

algorithms were applied.


\section{miRNA target gene identification}
\label{sec:mirna-target-gene-identification}

Four up-regulated miRNAs (hsa-miR-210-3p, hsa-miR-183-5p, hsa-miR-21-5p, hsa-miR-181b-

5p) were subjected to target prediction. The mRNA targets of these four up-regulated miRNAs

from TCGA were predicted using four in silico miRNA target prediction tools (TargetScan \cite{abudour2024role} ,

MiRanda \cite{agosta2018promote} , RNAhybrid \cite{abudour2024role} , Pictar \cite{agosta2018promote} ). Experimentally validated MTI pairs were curated

using the miRTarBase \cite{abudour2024role} . To further screen potential direct targets, various criteria were

employed. Specifically, a MiRanda score of $\geq$ 140, a MiRanda minimum free energy (MFE) of

$\leq$ -10, and a TargetScan seed type of $\geq$ 7mer-A1 \cite{abudour2024role} for predicted targets were considered


favorable choices. Using miRTarBase \cite{abudour2024role} , experimentally validated miRNA-target gene

interaction pairs were curated, excluding those that have already been experimentally confirmed.

The remaining miRNA-target gene interaction pairs were selected for further analysis.


\section{Identification of the MTI prognostic risk model}
\label{sec:identification-of-the-mti-prognostic-ris}

We evaluated the correlation between mRNA and miRNA expression data using the Spearman

correlation coefficient ($\rho_{(i,j)}$). A prognosis prediction model was developed using the formula:

% TODO-MATH: formula below has garbled PDF encoding - needs manual LaTeX
% ORIG: risk score (RS) = $\sum$(𝐶𝐶𝐶𝐶𝐶𝐶𝐶𝐶 𝑘𝑘 $\times$ (exp(𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚 𝑖𝑖 ) $\times$ exp (𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚𝑚 𝑗𝑗 )) $\times$ 𝜌𝜌 𝑖𝑖,𝑗𝑗 . The prediction ability of the

MTI prognostic risk model was assessed by the receiver operating characteristics curve (ROC)

and area under the ROC curve (AUC). With the MTI prognostic model, the TNBC patients were

divided into low- and high-RS groups based on the cutoff value generated by KMeans based on

the risk score and survival outcome of patients. The associations between disease-free survival

(DFS) and OS miRNA expression levels were estimated by the Kaplan-Meier method and log-

rank test (Mantel-Cox).


