\subsection{Results}
\label{sec:results}

The machine learning pipeline identified four hub miRNAs with robust prognostic significance:

miR-181b-5p, miR-21-5p, miR-210-3p, and miR-183-5p. All four miRNAs showed significant

differential expression in TNBC compared to normal tissue and demonstrated univariate

association with overall survival. These miRNAs represent established oncogenic or tumor-

suppressive factors with documented roles in breast cancer biology, supporting their biological

relevance as prognostic indicators.


\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{fig-chp3-p028_00.png}
  \caption{Figure 5.  Identifications of DEmiRs and DEGs. (A) Volcano plot of miRNA differential}
  \label{fig:identifications-of-demirs-and-degs-a}
\end{figure}

expression in TNBC samples; (B) Volcano plot of mRNA differential expression in TNBC

samples; (C) Heatmap of miRNA differential expression between TNBC samples and normal


samples; (D) Heatmap of mRNA differential expression between TNBC samples and normal

samples; (E) GO functional enrichment for differentially expressed mRNAs. Left: Top 10 bar

chart of GO biological processes analysis; Right: Bar chart of GO molecular functions analysis.

Target prediction and validation yielded eight high-confidence target genes regulated by the four

hub miRNAs. From the 32 possible miRNA-target combinations, we identified 19 pairs with

experimental validation support from published studies. Statistical analysis of MTI scores

identified ten pairs with significant prognostic association, forming the feature set for MTI-

based modeling. The resulting regulatory network reveals a complex architecture of overlapping

target regulation among the hub miRNAs.

The MTI-based model significantly outperformed the expression-based model across all

evaluation metrics. In the TCGA training cohort, the MTI model achieved a C-index of 0.74

compared to 0.65 for the expression model. Time-dependent AUC showed consistent

advantages for MTI-based prediction across multiple time horizons. Kaplan-Meier analysis

demonstrated that the MTI model provided stronger survival stratification, with greater

separation between high-risk and low-risk patient groups.


