GSE19783 cohorts; (E) Kaplan-Meier survival curves for high- and low-risk groups in the

GSE19783 validation cohort; (F) ROC curve of the 10 MTI correlation-based model in the

GSE19783 dataset.

Network analysis revealed 71 coherent feed-forward loops involving transcription factors, hub

miRNAs, and their shared target genes. In these regulatory circuits, a transcription factor

simultaneously regulates both the miRNA and the target gene, creating coordinated and robust

regulatory control. The identification of these network motifs provides mechanistic context for

the observed prognostic associations and suggests that the MTI-based approach captures

biologically meaningful regulatory architecture.


\subsection{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

The superior performance of MTI-based prognostic modeling has important implications for

clinical biomarker development. By quantifying regulatory relationships rather than molecular

abundances, edge-based approaches capture the functional output of miRNA activity. This

functional information is directly relevant to patient outcomes, as it reflects the downstream

transcriptomic consequences of miRNA regulation. The success of this approach in TNBC

suggests that edge-based biomarkers may offer advantages across cancer types characterized by

molecular heterogeneity.

A key advantage of MTI-based analysis is its robustness against the biological heterogeneity

that confounds expression-based biomarkers. Expression levels are influenced by numerous

factors including tumor cellularity, microenvironmental composition, and technical variables,

contributing to poor cross-cohort reproducibility. Regulatory relationships, in contrast, represent

stable functional connections that persist across these sources of variation. The improved

generalization of the MTI model to an independent cohort demonstrates this robustness,


supporting the utility of edge-based biomarkers for clinical translation.


\section{Case II: Resolving the Context Dependency via Network Topology}
\label{sec:case-ii-resolving-the-context-dependenc}


\subsection{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

MiR-483 presents a striking functional paradox that challenges simple interpretations of miRNA

biology [43-45] . In cancer contexts, miR-483 consistently acts as an oncogene, promoting tumor

cell proliferation, inhibiting apoptosis, and correlating with poor patient prognosis across

multiple malignancies including hepatocellular carcinoma, colorectal cancer, and Wilms tumor

[46-55] . However, in cardiovascular and metabolic diseases, the same miRNA functions as a

protector, preventing cardiac fibrosis, ameliorating diabetic nephropathy, and conferring

resistance to tissue injury [56-63] . This duality cannot be explained by differences in miR-483

sequence or expression level, which remain constant across contexts.

We hypothesized that the functional paradox of miR-483 could be explained by differences in

network topology across disease contexts. Specifically, we proposed that while miR-483

modulates a shared set of core signaling pathways, the dominant regulatory connections,

determined by tissue-specific expression of targets and co-regulator, differ across contexts,

leading to opposite functional outcomes. This hypothesis implies that function is not intrinsic to

the miRNA sequence but emerges from the network architecture in which the miRNA operates.


\subsection{Materials and Methods}
\label{sec:materials-and-methods}

We performed comprehensive literature curation to compile experimentally validated regulatory

relationships involving miR-483. We systematically searched PubMed for studies reporting

miR-483 interactions, extracting information on regulatory partners, interaction directionality,

experimental validation methods, and disease context. This process yielded 146 studies

providing validated interactions across multiple biological contexts. All curated interactions

were annotated with evidence quality scores based on validation methodology.


We constructed a comprehensive multi-layer regulatory network centered on miR-483. The

upstream layer incorporated transcription factors regulating miR-483 expression, using data

from our miRStart 2.0 platform supplemented by literature-curated TF-miRNA relationships.

Additional upstream regulators including long non-coding RNAs (lncRNAs) and circular RNAs

(circRNAs) that sponge or modulate miR-483 activity were included [64-73] . The downstream

layer comprised validated target genes with their associated pathway annotations. This multi-

layer architecture captures the complete regulatory context of miR-483.

